courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of this course students should be able to:

1. identify different phenomena related to consciousness and the philosophical and social issues involved;

2. evaluate the scientific thinking and research tools used to test theories about consciousness;

3. reflect on the philosophical and ethical issues in the use of our knowledge about consciousness, in areas such as lie detection, subliminal advertising, hypnosis and meditation, etc.

4. demonstrate the ability to communicate to others their evaluations and reflections as stated in 2 and 3 above.

Upon completion of this course, students will be expected to:
1. appreciate the impacts of the existing cases of psychology applications;
2. broaden and deepen their understanding of the rationale and impacts of the existing cases of psychology applications;
3. understand, relate, and apply the psychological concepts to create changes on some problems in the real life;
4. emerge from the course with innovative and realistic ideas to implement their knowledge, skills, and values in psychology in applied settings;
5. understand and reflect on the ethical issues involved in applied work; AND
6. conceptualize, structure, articulate and present original ideas both in written assignments and during weekly discussions.

